segments.text: the 12th, testing, testing.
Okay, am I speaking here?
I'm testing also, and got a frog in my voice it sounds like, but I think I'll work through it.
This is March the 12th, and we're at 1709 Glade, and I have the honor and joy of chatting with Robert Spode, S-P-O-D-E. No, S-P-O-E-D-E. Oh, S-P-O-E-D, oh, thank you, thank you.
German umlaut, old German umlaut.
Oh.
What does that mean in German?
Do you know?
I have no idea.
We're searching and searching.
Cannot find it.
Quite possibly has something to do with ashes from which you make china, porcelain, and stuff like that.
We wonder if there's a relationship with Spode China in England.
And my grandfather's citizen papers had SVO .
To introduce yourself to anyone who would read this transcript or hear this tape,
Tell us about your family background.
Give us a brief biographical sketch of you until you came to A&M.
Where'd you grow up and family and so forth?
I was born in a farm out in the midst of the cotton patch in Austin County near the hamlet or village of Wallace, Texas.
My parents at that time were sharecropping farmers for their
on land owned by their parents, my father's parents, who were German.
And they had about four farms that they had.
They shared the produce and the crops on.
My family, my background and lineage is that of German, basically peasant Germans who came over here at 1880 as teenagers and met over here in the vicinity of New York.
One was my grandmother was Catholic, my grandfather was Protestant, Lutheran.
They got married.
Many interesting things there, but they were successful in a truck farm about where Meadowlands football field is now.
And my father used to tell them, taking the truck with the produce over to the markets in New York City.
But anyway, they sold that farm, came around by boat to Galveston,
in Austin County and bought land from my mother's parents who had come into Texas about 1855 in Wallace, Texas and established there.
Then when I was six years old, we moved across the Gracious River from Austin County into Fort Bend County where my father there was sharecropping land owned by my mother's father.
Now he had a much larger holding.
He had about 1400 acres and had about 10 acres
sharecroppers, 10, 11, 12 sharecroppers.
Now, these were basically Mexican sharecroppers.
What was the money crop then?
Cotton.
Cotton.
You grew almost most of the cotton, a little bit of corn.
Then you grew vegetables for your own use and cows and pigs and stuff like that.
And the railroad ran through that area by then?
The railroad went through there.
In fact, the town of Wallace, Hamlet, could well have been named for my mother's family, Giler.
because they gave a good portion of the land of the town when they built the railroad through there.
And it moved Beaubing Bend, Texas, which was on the Brazos River, over into along the railroad.
And Beaubing Bend, of course, no longer exists.
And it was from there that my mother's father left home in 1878 by ox cart and driven.
And there is an article.
way back about him, written by him on his trip to A&M.
It was written for the Texas Ivy publication.
It wasn't the magazine it is now.
It was pulp paper.
And coming there with his black hooker to pop the fly off of an ox, you know, with his whip and so on.
They went to Hockley and there he got on the train and came to A&M on the train in 1878.
Now with him,
He did not finish A&M because he got in a knife fight as about a 14-year-old.
He was about 14.
It was a three-year curriculum.
A&M was then really kind of a high school for him.
And he got in a knife fight and had to drop out of school.
But he loved A&M all the years of his life.
Are you saying N-I-G-H-T, knight, or K-N-I-F-E?
Knife fight.
A knife fight.
K-N-I-F-E. Yeah, with knives.
With knives.
Was anybody hurt, or do you know?
He was hurt.
I don't know who else was hurt.
But he was a violent man.
He was a, I know he killed at least one man later on.
Was he, in today's terminology, did he have an academic major?
I don't know.
He was, but he loved history, loved learning.
It demonstrated to me and incited an interest in me because he named his horses Saxon and, what was the other one?
There's another, one of the other Germanic tribes.
Mm-hmm.
Not Engle, but Saxon and something else.
Vandals, Saxon and Vandals.
So he was here almost three years?
No, about one year.
Oh, one year.
He was here at the same time, probably the same.
Houston's son was here.
And, of course, everybody lived on the campus.
Lived on the campus.
Lived in Gayford Hall at that time.
But, in fact, he was a high school student.
Really a high school student.
He was born in April of 1865, and he enrolled in, I guess, fall of 1878.
So you figure out he was about 13.
Did you hear any stories about how he got to college, got to the campus, and did he always go by cart or wagon?
I don't know how he got back.
No, I don't know.
No, I didn't.
Any family souvenirs, keepsakes from him?
I was the youngest grandson.
His son and his son's son were the first three-generation family to come in here.
None of them graduated.
I and my brother were the second and third.
Many of our family came in here who ever graduated.
So you're his grandson.
I'm his grandson.
Okay, he goes back into farming.

He goes back into farming and he also had a general store and his farming when I was in doctoral program they talked about how did they keep the plantations going and the way they described was exactly he had a commissary in his backyard when I knew him and
His tenants would come in and buy on credit from the commissary, and then when the cotton was sold, they would settle their accounts and have nothing.
And his tenants were Hispanic, were Mexican-American.
Right, right, not black.
And then my father and my mother, but there's a lot of story that he promised him 200 acres of land or something, but he never came through with it.
Now, did your dad come to A&M?
My dad never finished high school.
His father thought seventh grade education was enough for any former.
He was going to be a former.
And he never finished high school.
But he did marry my mother, who had gone to CIA, College of Industrial Arts.
It didn't later, Texas State College of Women.
Now, Texas Women's University, Sister's School, A&M.
And she had a certificate.
That was a three-year program, too, when she went there.
And she didn't have a bachelor's, but she could teach school.
And she helped him a lot.
And he, World War I, he was drafted and won the Army and was selected for also Kennedy School, because he could name the equivalent ranks in the Navy to the Army.
It was a big thing.
And got a commission.
And during the 20s and 30s, he went back to farming.
And in the 20s and 30s, he kept his commission active.
And then in 1936, he was called to the Army.
And we moved from Simonton, Texas, where I started school two years, first and second grade in a two-room schoolhouse, grades one to six there, and moved to Lufkin.
Then we moved to Waco, all transferred by the CCC, then to Marshall, Texas, then to Fort Worth, Texas, and that's where we worked when Pearl Harbor started.
And he was called to active duty, I mean, with active army, and went to San Antonio, where he was pro-Marshall,
of wartime San Antonio, 500,000, and he had to keep order downtown San Antonio, and with no, no police experience, no college degree.
But he did a good job, and he was chosen to be the technical expert for a training field called town patrolling.
And he went to Hollywood.
We can't imagine my father in Hollywood.
All right, so you're in high school at Jefferson?
I was in high school at San Antonio, graduated in June the 3rd, I think, 1944, Friday night.
Sunday, we were at A&M.
My best friend and I came to A&M on that, and we came in his parents' car, pre-war car, not big, and all of our possessions
were in the trunk of that car for two of us.
Maybe a little radio, I don't know.
So you enrolled in the summer school?
We came and we were enrolling on D-Day.

Our class was very proud of the fact that, and I was, with my interest in current events, history, I was about to go crazy because I could hear the radios talking about the invasion, you know, and I had to stand in line.
What do you think was the attitude of your buddies and everybody else about whether or not D-Day would succeed?
Were Americans optimistic?
We assumed it would.
We were optimistic, for sure.
Then never dreamt it not succeeding.
I mean, that was the first time it ever crossed my mind.
I'm looking back, you know, that there was... My dad was...
woodworker in the shipyard in Orange.
And we're driving back to Garland to visit family.
And I've got the radio on the whole time.
And that night, my grandmother let me sleep on a pallet in the living room.
And I put the radio right near my pillow and turned it and listened to it all night.
And I particularly remember some of the famous radio voices giving live reports.
Here comes a dive bomber.
Here comes a this.
Here comes a that.
Well, I did that with Edward R. Murrow, a reporter from London, in describing the fight that won the Fair Plains, you know.
Let's back up.
When did you get the encouragement to go to college?
How early did you, now in hindsight, realize that you were destined to go to college?
at the earliest possible time, when you even begin to think about that, it was a given from, I guess, from my mother.
My father also, he wanted to go to A&M.

If he could have gone to school, and he loved the school, and the juncture of being a reserve officer and forming, coming together in the Corps of Cadets, and marrying the daughter of a person who loved this school dearly,
and who, in fact, has the oldest foundation, and the former students is, I think, Hibbs.
And his name's not very big, you know, about $2,000.
But I think it's the oldest one there.
But he loved this school.
They all did.
All right.
When you came to enroll that summer, what did you bring physically?
What stuff did you have?
Some underwear, some civilian clothes, not much.
Maybe two days of clothing at the most, three days, I mean.
You said maybe a radio.
Maybe a radio.
Any other?
Well, I wasn't shaving yet, so I didn't have to bring any razor or anything.
Probably, I guess I brought a toothbrush.
Not much.
I mean, not very much.
Do you remember your parents or anyone else giving you any last-minute advice, counsel?
No.
I was a very compliant boy.
Very obedient.
That never gave them any trouble.
I get very much a family thing here.
I'd seen my mother cry an awful lot from phone calls.
And I was the youngest of three boys.
And I never wanted her to get a phone call
from me or about me that made her cry.
I've had enough of that.
And so, if she told me to be in at 10 o'clock, I was in at 10 o'clock.
Not only she didn't, she wasn't that restrictive, if you don't understand me, but I was very compliant.
I've always been very compliant.
Therefore, I had no trouble at A&M as a patient.
Why did you come to summer school instead of waiting for the fall?
Well, when I finished high school, my brother had been lost as a Marine Corps fighter pilot off Guadalcanal.
And I wanted to join the Marines.
So my folks, I wanted to join the Marines as soon as I graduated.
My mother, having lost one son, asked me, she said, Robert, would you please get one semester of college in?
And at that time, me and Amber ran three semesters in one year.
And...
I said, all right.
They said, you can get a summer semester in before you turn 18.
I did not want to sign up for the draft.
I was super patriotic, I think.
And to sign up for the draft meant I was going reluctantly.
And I did not want that on my record, so I never wanted to be eligible for the draft.
So I wanted to sign up when I was 17.
And they lived up to theirs.
I lived up to mine.
And I went down to San Antonio and signed up.
And when I got through, the officer there said, recommend you go back to college because we've got 55 people ahead of you.
And we think you can never get another semester in.
And so I went back to college as a Marine Corps private reserve.
and got all but two weeks of the fall semester, and the college gave me credit for the semester.
All right, back to that summer.
Was it pretty well a full semester in terms of the number of students?
Was it a big number?
We have a very small class.
I'm class co-agent of my class now, and it's the most we ever had in the class, and that's counting some that came in in August and September.

kind of son who came in immediately at the war and went through real quickly and graduated in 48 and some transfer to graduate in 48 and the total class at the biggest was 900 the total number of the class alright describe y'all you came with this friend and y'all drive up where did you go to to kind of report we got a letter

Parents got a letter, bring your darling, I mean, I'm paraphrasing, putting some other words in there, bring your darling little boy to campus, open the car doors, put his baggage out, put him on the curb, kiss him goodbye, get back in your car, and leave him in our tender mercies.
And Mr. and Mrs. Lane did that.

and we were left standing there, and we knew where our dorm was, which was Walton Hall, and we wandered over there, I guess, and immediately we were in the tender mercies of the sophomores and juniors.
But I came to A&M with my best friend, which was a big asset, because there was a little touch of home there, and it made it easier.
Had you visited the campus before that?
Oh, yes.
Sorry.
Well, yes.
First time I visited campus, 1936, my father brought me over from Lufkin, Texas to a football game in which Dick Todd was a sophomore for A&M and playing against Sammy Ball, who was a senior at TCU.
A&M won that game, but next year got clobbered real bad.
No, two years later got clobbered real bad, but that was the first time.
Then my brother came.
his freshman year, and he lived in the corner ramp of Puryear Hall, no longer existing.
And we drove up and parked there on that street that was in front of Puryear Hall.
And I went in, and all of these people started introducing themselves to me.
I was a 12-year-old.
I'm Fish so-and-so.
I'm Fish Gillis.
My brother's roommate was Tom Gillis.
And I'm Fish Gillis.
I'm Fish so-and-so.
And I went back out of the car and said, Mom, what kind of place is this?
Everybody here is named Fish.
But that was 1938.
But I was taken in, and I go to football games with my brother, Stan, with the Corps of Cadets, and Saul washed his hands off, and I got totally, completely brainwashed.
And this is what I wanted, to be part of the brotherhood.
fellowship.
So you arrived that summer.
You already knew what dorm you were going to be.
Describe how you and this friend, how did you all get blended into that dorm and into that outfit?
What outfit were you in?
I was in A battery field artillery.
The battery commander was named Builderback.
There were two Builderbacks.
One was the track man.
This was not the track man.
He was the
veterinarian student, and the executive officer of the battery was Mr.
Spear.
We had a fellow from down in Duval County named Parr, which we had a nickname for.
I better not use it here, but it has to do with a part of the sexual and alliteration organs.
But he was a sophomore, and he was a kind of a mean one.
The later I called on our battery commander, who's now a veterinarian, but he's paraplegic.
And I went to San Antonio to see if we bought him one time, and looked him up.
And I asked him, I said, how did we end up at being your room art lease?
He said, I've selected you as your roommate.
And so we were his room art lease, which was a big, big, big asset.
I mean, Mr. Park came to us and told us to do something.
Sorry, sir, I'm on detail from Mr.
Builder back.
And he was a kind of a protector, being room orderly to him.
I like to talk about room orderly business sometimes.
I do.
And it was, several things happened.
Number one, we were there.
I like to talk, why did I come to A&M?
I came to A&M as I guess an anthropologist would call it a rite of passage.
to see if I could take it.
I knew what A&M was.
My brothers had been here.
I knew about the hazing.
I wanted the hazing.
I wanted it.
I wanted that year.
Just test my mettle.
I figured that doing it remotely for one year and getting it for three years was a pretty good deal.
But there were things that happened.
My father broke a relationship with a man.
Maybe you don't want to use the name because he's a local fellow here.
He probably has relatives here, but I will name him.
You can cut it out later if you want to.
Captain Joe Falk was a tech officer here.
Joe Falk was a friend of my father's from CCC days.
And he came to my father and says, Herman, get Robert to tell you what's going on in the outfit, and we'll get rid of those upperclassmen who were having to perform with Marguerite.
My father never spoke to him again in his life.
And they called Captain Hank up.
hiding.
A freshman lifted the lid of a garbage can.
There was a captain in there trying to find him.
It just was ridiculous.
Most of us were getting a little fine and didn't want to do it.
I'll go back.
I'm talking here.
They gave us that letter and told us to leave.
Everybody did that except one set of parents.
I'll name his name.
His name was Fish Helbig.
He ended up in my outfit.

And his parents stood in line, all these long lines, to register and get, you know, do all of that, and stood out like a sore thumb, because there were other parents that just dropped us off and gone home.
Well, Fish Hellwick was in and out, but he got hazed a lot more than I did, because, as I said, I'm a good, compliant boy, and I had nobody.
But he got hazed, and he wrote along and told his parents about it, how they were getting him up and doing everything, and do sit-ups and push-ups and so forth at 2 o'clock in the morning,
And his mother sent a letter to some administrator at A&M.
And then all of a sudden we had a big battery meeting.
And so and so and so and so and so and so had been dismissed from the Corps and had to be day dodgers now.
And it was a real, real cold.
I mean, it was the first time I'd ever been in a meeting like that.
Very somber.
Now, did those activities that
today we'd call hazing, did that begin almost immediately?
Immediately.
Immediately.
How long was it before classes began?
After you arrived?
Very quickly.
During the summer, since this was three semesters year-round, was that summer semester Monday, Wednesday, Friday, Tuesday, Thursday, Saturday classes?
Yes, it was when I came back.
Until 49.
About how many hours did you take that first semester?
I think I took 17 hours.
And what was your major at that time?
At that time, it was civil engineering.
Go back.
Why did you pick that?
When I finished high school, if you had asked me, what is your ambition?
And if I'd been honest, though most high school students, it's harder than being absolutely honest.
I always said my ambition is to be a Texas Aggie.
My immediate ambition is to be a Texas Aggie.
Well, to go to A&M, I knew with my interest and aptitude that I should go to that school 90 miles west of here.
I knew I loved words, I loved reading, I loved literature, I loved history, but I'd rather have been dead than go to that school.
So I wanted to be a Texas Aggie.
And if you go to A&M, well, you should.
really ought to major something he was fairly good at, engineering, agriculture, something like that.
Which, okay, which is the broadest of the engineering?
Civil engineering.
So I'll go and major in civil engineering.
And I got here and pick up my, all my books and I get my history book and read it, all of it, all the way through the first two books.
About a minute later I said, this is ridiculous.
I can do this engineering, but yuck.
I don't like it.
Not interesting.
You spend too much time in labs for the credits you get.
I mean, I go three hours to history class and English class and get three hours of credit.
I go to three hours of chemistry and then four hours of lab and get four hours of credit.
That's a bump, you know.
But I like the history, so I said, I don't care if any of them is good in history or not good in history.
I'm going to major in history.
And what did you think you were going to do with that history degree?
At the first, I thought I probably would have to teach history.
And then, while I was here, it came back from the Marines, one or much other.
Now, go back to about fourth grade, when I was in Texas one time, I remember these things.
A teacher came in and said, what's your ambition?

My father, whom I loved and admired, was a wonderful man, was a captain of the reserves, but I could tell around the table he could be relieved from active duty at any time, and we were back on the farm.
We had nothing.
And by their conversation, I knew that they really envied the people who had the security of a regular Army commission.
And so I wanted to be like him, a captain, but I wanted to be a captain, one step up, a regular Army.
I said, I want to be a captain of the regular army.
She really got on me.
She said, why do you want to be such a bum?
I mean, she really rented out.
She had cancer somewhere or something, a piece of it.
And she said that.
So one of my things was captain of the regular army.
I dreamt of having a regular army commission.
The only other school I thought about at the first point, even remotely.
That first semester, did you have some, do you remember some of the teachers, courses, et cetera you had that first semester?
Were some of those important to you in the long run that you now realize?
Only Dr. Chemistry later present me and him.
Harrington?
Harrington.
He was a wonderful friend of the cadets.
Describe him as a teacher.
Just, to me, just easygoing and understanding and fun.
But one thing I do remember that
We sat in that chemistry building, and I did not know that I was nearsighted.
And they set us by alphabetical order.
And I ended up at the back of the chemistry building, of the chemistry lecture room.
And I could not see what he was writing on the blackboard.
And I never did learn to do balance equations in chemistry.
But I managed to get by with a C somehow.
But let me see.
Later on, when I came back, I remember them much better.
But I don't remember that.
In fact, my mind, since I was going and going to Marines, my freshman grades don't show very good at all.
But you passed everything.
I passed everything.
In fact, my weapon of great point went down from high school, as did all the Thomas Jefferson people.
My grade points...
One up, rather, from what we've done in high school.
And Jefferson was a great high school at that time.
Absolutely fabulous.
About how many in your senior class?
At Jefferson, 555 graduated.
Yeah.
And they had two graduations a year.
Describe, beginning that summer, describe a typical class day for an Aggie Fish in the summer of 44, is that right?
Summer of 44.
What time did y'all get up?
What did you do when?
Get up around, I assume, six o'clock.
Clean up our room.
We're done cleaning up the upper-classes room at that time.
Fall out for formation.
And you'd fall out where?
It depends on which dorm we were in.
If we were in what we called the new area, the first time we'd fall out in front of Walton Hall and march to Sevesa.
Then we'd eat and table service.
A lot of guys were working their way through A&M simply by waiting on tables in the dining halls and get through.
and give all the good stuff, meal service to the upperclassmen.
They got first, pretty much first pick.
And use all this language and learn that stuff.
And I don't remember eating at a brace that we may have, but I don't remember doing it.
And going back and cleaning up, making sure our room was spotless, and the upperclassmen room was spotless, Mr. Bailback, Mr. Spears room was spotless.
empty their garbage and all that good stuff.
Then at 8 o'clock, go to our first class.
Then about 9 o'clock, generally speaking in the morning, go across the railroad tracks.
We had PE three times a week.
It was more like basic training.
As I said in a, talking to kids from Muster when we had our 50th anniversary class, I said in one quarter basic training in three quarters academic institution.
There was survival at sea and PE when your ship, not if your ship got sunk, but when your ship got sunk.
How to make a flotation device out of your trousers.
Mr. Art Adamson did that.
Then we'd go over to the Tender Mercies of Mr. Penberthy and Mr. Putnam.
And that was the other time.
